violations.llm_prompt:
WHAT: api/ struct fields must be trait objects (Arc<dyn Trait> or Box<dyn Trait>) or value types — not concrete domain structs from other layers.
WHY: A concrete domain struct as a field tightly couples the api/ struct to that struct's definition; if the impl struct adds/removes fields, the api/ struct's memory layout changes, breaking callers.
BEFORE (violation):
  // api/types/pipeline.rs
  pub struct Pipeline { processor: crate::core::DefaultProcessor } // concrete domain struct as field
AFTER (compliant):
  use std::sync::Arc;
  pub struct Pipeline { processor: Arc<dyn ProcessorTrait> } // trait object — hides the concrete impl
  impl Pipeline {
      pub fn new(processor: Arc<dyn ProcessorTrait>) -> Self { Self { processor } }
  }
EDGE CASES:
  - Standard value types (String, u64, PathBuf, Vec<T>): these are value types, not domain structs — allowed
  - Newtypes declared in api/types/: also allowed since they are api/-owned with no impl details
  - Box<dyn Trait> vs Arc<dyn Trait>: both satisfy the rule — use Arc when shared ownership is needed, Box for single ownership

