WHAT: The E in `Result<T, E>` for pub trait methods in api/ must be a named local error enum — String, &str, Box<dyn Error>, anyhow::Error, and eyre::Report are all banned.

WHY: Opaque error types prevent callers from exhaustively matching on failure modes. They also expose implementation choices (e.g. anyhow) as part of the public contract, making the contract hard to stabilise.

BEFORE (violating):
  // api/traits/parser.rs
  pub trait Parser {
      fn parse(&self, input: &str) -> Result<Ast, String>;  // ❌ opaque E
  }

AFTER (compliant):
  // api/errors/parse_error.rs
  #[derive(Debug, thiserror::Error)]
  pub enum ParseError { #[error("invalid input: {0}")] InvalidInput(String) }

  // api/traits/parser.rs
  pub trait Parser {
      fn parse(&self, input: &str) -> Result<Ast, ParseError>;  // ✅
  }

EDGE CASES:
- The named error must be local to THIS crate's api/ — re-exporting an upstream crate's error type is not acceptable (declare a wrapper enum instead).
- `anyhow::Error` is banned even if the method is only called internally; the trait signature is the contract.

