WHAT: In api/ trait methods returning `Result<T, E>`, BOTH T and E must be named local types — a mixed shape (named T, opaque E, or vice versa) is banned.

WHY: Even one opaque side breaks the contract: callers cannot match on an unnamed error, and a primitive T cannot be extended. Both sides must be stable named types.

BEFORE (violating):
  // api/traits/processor.rs
  pub trait Processor {
      fn run(&self, input: Input) -> Result<ProcessResponse, String>;  // ❌ named T, opaque E
      fn count(&self) -> Result<u64, ProcessError>;                    // ❌ opaque T, named E
  }

AFTER (compliant):
  pub trait Processor {
      fn run(&self, input: Input) -> Result<ProcessResponse, ProcessError>;  // ✅ both named
      fn count(&self) -> Result<(), ProcessError>;                           // ✅ () allowed for T
  }

EDGE CASES:
- `Result<(), E>` is the only exception for T — unit return for side-effect-only operations does not need a wrapper struct.
- This rule fires even when `trait_result_named_error` and `trait_result_named_response` both pass individually, because the combined check catches asymmetric patterns those rules may miss.

