violations.llm_prompt:
WHAT: Every `pub fn` with a `self` receiver in an api/ pub trait must accept exactly one parameter whose type ends with `Request`.

WHY: Multiple naked parameters make signatures fragile — adding a field is a breaking change. A single `*Request` struct is an extension point: new optional fields can be added without touching the trait signature.

BEFORE (violating):
  pub trait UserService {
      fn create(&self, name: String, email: String, role: Role) -> ...;  // ❌ three loose params
      fn count(&self) -> ...;                                             // ❌ no param at all
  }

AFTER (compliant):
  // api/types/create_user_request.rs
  pub struct CreateUserRequest { pub name: String, pub email: String, pub role: Role }

  pub trait UserService {
      fn create(&self, req: CreateUserRequest) -> ...;  // ✅ single Request
      fn count(&self, req: CountRequest) -> ...;        // ✅ even count gets a Request
  }

EDGE CASES:
- Static methods (no self receiver) are exempt.
- The `*Request` type must be declared in api/types/, not inline or in core/.
- A request with a single field is still preferable over a bare parameter — it names the concept.

