WHAT: api/ files must not contain impl blocks — api/ is a pure declaration layer (traits, types, error structs; no logic).
WHY: impl blocks in api/ embed behavior beside the contract; consumers can call implementation-specific logic through the abstraction layer, and changes to that logic break the contract unexpectedly.
BEFORE (violation):
  // api/types/config.rs
  pub struct Config { pub timeout_ms: u64 }
  impl Config { pub fn validate(&self) -> bool { self.timeout_ms > 0 } } // impl in api/
AFTER (compliant):
  // api/types/config.rs — pure declaration
  pub struct Config { pub timeout_ms: u64 }
  // core/config_validator.rs — logic lives in core/
  impl Config { pub(crate) fn validate(&self) -> bool { self.timeout_ms > 0 } }
EDGE CASES:
  - `impl Default for MyStruct`: move to core/ even though Default is a stdlib trait
  - `impl Display for ErrorType`: move to core/ alongside the type's Display logic
  - Builder pattern: if api/ has `impl Builder { fn build() }`, move to core/ or saf/

