WHAT: Every method on every pub trait in api/ must have three test functions in tests/: one _happy, one _error, and one _edge — exercised through a test-double implementation of the trait.

WHY: api/ traits define the architecture's contracts. Verifying every method under happy, error, and edge conditions proves the contract is implementable, handles all inputs correctly, and does not rely on accidental behaviour of a single concrete implementation.

BEFORE (violating):
  // main/src/api/traits.rs
  pub trait Scanner {
      fn scan(&self, path: &Path) -> Result<Vec<File>>;
  }
  // ❌ tests/ has no _happy/_error/_edge tests for Scanner::scan

AFTER (compliant):
  // tests/scanner_int_test.rs
  struct TestScanner;
  impl Scanner for TestScanner {
      fn scan(&self, path: &Path) -> Result<Vec<File>> {
          if path.exists() { Ok(vec![]) } else { Err(ReviewError::path("not found")) }
      }
  }

  /// @covers: check_core_impl_tests_colocated
  #[test]
  fn test_scan_existing_path_happy() {
      assert!(TestScanner.scan(Path::new(".")).is_ok());   // ✅
  }

  /// @covers: check_core_impl_tests_colocated
  #[test]
  fn test_scan_missing_path_error() {
      assert!(TestScanner.scan(Path::new("/no/such")).is_err());   // ✅
  }

  /// @covers: check_core_impl_tests_colocated
  #[test]
  fn test_scan_empty_dir_edge() {
      let dir = tempdir().unwrap();
      assert_eq!(TestScanner.scan(dir.path()).unwrap().len(), 0);   // ✅
  }

EDGE CASES:
- Tests use a TestImpl (struct implementing the trait), not the real DefaultImpl, so the contract itself is verified independently of any concrete implementation.
- If a trait method has no error return type (returns a non-Result), replace the _error test with a second _edge test for a different boundary condition.

