WHAT: Every submodule declared in api/mod.rs must have a matching submodule declaration in core/mod.rs.

WHY: An api/ domain without an implementation home indicates a structural gap — new contracts were added but no one created the implementation skeleton, leaving the domain only partially wired.

BEFORE (violating):
  // api/mod.rs
  pub mod events;   // declared  ✅
  pub mod metrics;  // declared

  // core/mod.rs
  pub(crate) mod events;  // present
  // metrics missing       ❌

AFTER (compliant):
  // core/mod.rs
  pub(crate) mod events;
  pub(crate) mod metrics;  // ✅ added

  // core/metrics/mod.rs created (may start as a stub)

EDGE CASES:
- The core/ mirror can start as an empty stub (`// TODO: implement`); the rule only checks that the module is declared, not that it contains real implementations.
- api/ modules that re-export from other crates (pure adapters) may legitimately have no core/ counterpart — check the module's purpose before adding a stub.

WHAT: Every public function in api/ must be verified by an external test file in tests/; inline #[cfg(test)] blocks in api/ source files are not sufficient for public functions.

WHY: api/ is the declared contract surface. Testing it externally (from tests/, which is a separate crate) exercises the actual public visibility and import path that consumers use. Inline tests bypass visibility constraints and cannot verify the public surface as a consumer would see it.

BEFORE (violating):
  // main/src/api/types/config.rs
  pub fn default_config() -> Config { ... }
  // ❌ only tested inline — no tests/api_config_int_test.rs

AFTER (compliant):
  // tests/api_config_int_test.rs   ✅
  use my_crate::default_config;   // import as external consumer

  /// @covers: default_config
  #[test]
  fn test_default_config_returns_valid_config_happy() {
      let c = default_config();
      assert!(!c.source_dir.is_empty());
  }

EDGE CASES:
- Trait default method implementations in api/traits.rs may have inline tests for the default logic specifically; this rule targets standalone pub fn items.
- If api/ has no standalone pub fn (only trait declarations), this rule does not fire.
